<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="389" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="389">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="389">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">Adult male.</emphasis>
General coloration of the body light brown. Length of forewings 6.8 mm (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">n</emphasis>
= 1), coloration similar to that of the body, with a soft darkening on the crossveins and a pale, subapical, transverse band.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="389">
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">Head</emphasis>
(Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Heads in dorsal view of the species of the Smicridea brasiliana group A Smicridea (Rhyacophylax) brasiliana B S. (R.) weidneri C S. (R.) vermiculata D S. (R.) atrobasis E S. (R.) nanda. Abbreviations: CSL length of the coronal suture, IOD interocular distance, MEW maximum eye width, MHW maximum head width. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.80961.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712814" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">1D</figureCitation>
). In dorsal view rectangular. Internal margins of the eyes, in dorsal view, concave, postgenal areas small, triangular. Interocular area trapezoidal. Interocular distance 2.6 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
shorter than MHW. Coronal suture 1 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
the length of IOD. Eyes slightly produced anteriorly, maximum eye width 3.25 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
shorter than MHW. Anterolateral setose warts present, very subtle, oval, bifid posteriorly. Posterior setose warts subtriangular. Maxillary palp formula: I-II-III-IV-V.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="389">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">Male genitalia</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Anterolateral margin of segment IX slightly rounded on the dorsal half (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Male genitalia of Smicridea (Rhyacophylax) nanda A segments IX, X, inferior appendages and phallus, lateral view B segments IX, X and inferior appendages, dorsal view C tip of the phallus, lateral view D tip of the phallus, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.80961.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712820" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">7A</figureCitation>
). Tergum of segment X subtriangular in lateral view, with rounded apex, dorsal and ventral margins straight, ventral one with a sclerotized H-shaped area directed anteriorly through segment IX; in dorsal view divided mesally into two subtriangular hemitergites with rounded apex and mesal margins straight (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Male genitalia of Smicridea (Rhyacophylax) nanda A segments IX, X, inferior appendages and phallus, lateral view B segments IX, X and inferior appendages, dorsal view C tip of the phallus, lateral view D tip of the phallus, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.80961.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712820" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">7B</figureCitation>
). Inferior appendages with two articules, curved mesally in dorsal view, basal article slightly widened distally, apical article narrow, short, apex pointed (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Male genitalia of Smicridea (Rhyacophylax) nanda A segments IX, X, inferior appendages and phallus, lateral view B segments IX, X and inferior appendages, dorsal view C tip of the phallus, lateral view D tip of the phallus, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.80961.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712820" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">7A, B</figureCitation>
). Phallus with long and tubular phallobase; basal portion slightly broad, bending ventrad mesally, distal part straight (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Male genitalia of Smicridea (Rhyacophylax) nanda A segments IX, X, inferior appendages and phallus, lateral view B segments IX, X and inferior appendages, dorsal view C tip of the phallus, lateral view D tip of the phallus, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.80961.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712820" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">7A</figureCitation>
); basal and dista parts of the phallus forming an angle of ~ 90°; dorsal periphallic cap present at midlength. Sclerotized part of ejaculatory duct curved dorsad at midlength; tip directed upwards in lateral view; with two dorsolateral elongated, oval plates in lateral view and two spine-like sclerites beneath them (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Male genitalia of Smicridea (Rhyacophylax) nanda A segments IX, X, inferior appendages and phallus, lateral view B segments IX, X and inferior appendages, dorsal view C tip of the phallus, lateral view D tip of the phallus, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.80961.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712820" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">7A, C, D</figureCitation>
). Endotheca wrinkled (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F7" captionText="Figure 7. Male genitalia of Smicridea (Rhyacophylax) nanda A segments IX, X, inferior appendages and phallus, lateral view B segments IX, X and inferior appendages, dorsal view C tip of the phallus, lateral view D tip of the phallus, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.80961.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712820" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">7D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption doi="10.3897/zookeys.1111.80961.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/712820" pageId="0" pageNumber="389" start="Figure 7" startId="F7">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="389">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">Figure 7.</emphasis>
Male genitalia of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Flint" authorityYear="1983" class="Insecta" family="Hydropsychidae" genus="Smicridea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Smicridea (Rhyacophylax) nanda" order="Trichoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="389" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nanda" subGenus="Rhyacophylax">Smicridea (Rhyacophylax) nanda</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">A</emphasis>
segments IX, X, inferior appendages and phallus, lateral view 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">B</emphasis>
segments IX, X and inferior appendages, dorsal view 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">C</emphasis>
tip of the phallus, lateral view 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">D</emphasis>
tip of the phallus, dorsal view.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="389" type="systematic considerations">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="389">Systematic considerations.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="389">
This species seems to be related to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="S." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="S. brasiliana" order="Trichoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="389" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brasiliana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">S. brasiliana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="S." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="S. weidneri" order="Trichoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="389" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="weidneri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">S. weidneri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see Systematic considerations section for 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" genus="S." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="S. brasiliana" order="Trichoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="389" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brasiliana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">S. brasiliana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Flint" authorityYear="1983" class="Insecta" family="Hydropsychidae" genus="Smicridea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Smicridea nanda" order="Trichoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="389" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nanda">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="389">Smicridea nanda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized by the ejaculatory duct that is curved dorsad at midlength and distally upturned, and the shape of the two pairs of sclerotized plates: the dorsolateral ones elongated, oval in lateral view and the other two spine-like lying beneath them.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
